<!-- Review Zone -->
<div class="review-text-zone">

<a href="album.asp?id=4197"><span style="font-weight:bold;font-size:13px">Illusions</span></a><br>
<a href="artist.asp?id=786">For Absent Friends</a> <span style="color:#777;font-size:9px;">Neo-Prog</span><br>

<p>Review by

<a href="Collaborators.asp?id=8096"><strong>Tarcisio Moura</strong></a>

<br><font color="#dc143c"><strong>Prog Reviewer</strong> <em></em></font>
</p>



<div style="color:#333;">


	<div class="avatarhp-box">
	<a href="https://www.progarchives.com/Collaborators.asp?id=8096">
	
	<img src="https://www.progarchives.com/forum/uploads/8096/unspoken_Whisper.jpg" class="avatarhp" width=100 onerror="this.src='http://www.progarchives.com/forum/avatars/blank_avatar.jpg'" />
	</a>
	</div>



<img src="static-images/3stars.gif" alt="3 stars" border="0">
Honestly, I´m still trying to find out why this dutch band is on the neo prog categorization. For
Absent Friends is not really even a progressive group: their name (bearing one of Genesis early
songs) is quite misleading. FAF plays a very sophisticated pop rock. It has some strong prog
influences, especially on the keyboards arrangements, very good. But clearly this is not a neo prog
band.  So if you´re looking for something like Marillion, Pendragon, IQ or Pallas, forget it. They
are nothing like that. Prog Related would be a more fitting label, I guess.<p>If you´re looking for melodic rock, well played, arranged and with strong songwriting, then you may
find something very interesting. Those 3 songs on this EP are very good and highly enjoyable.
Production could be a little better, but does not spoil the overall sound. If this was a straight
rock or AOR site this wold be a 4 star rating at least. For PA, 3 stars.</strong></strong></em></em>
</div>
</div>



